Anonymous Sat 28 Mar 2020 21:14:20 No.29256028 Report
Quoted By: >>29256267 >>29256598

Not him, but personally I'll have a concept for a story as a initial "Hey, wouldn't that be a cool idea?", think about what characters I'll need to tell that story, usually just anon and [insert anthro gal here], with maybe another few characters in the mix if I need aspects of one of the main characters fleshed out, (which even this I'll frequently make up characters on the spot if they're needed, and try and not just bang out random characters willy-nilly), a general narrative structure (this is where I want the story to go), and that's about it. Maybe at the absolute most I'll write down plot beats as just a few general words about it per point,
>anon goes to the shop and picks up X
>[insert anthro gal here] goes to anons because broken camera
that sort of thing, if a story is particularly long and it'll take a while to write it out, so it all stays straight over the weeks or likely months it'll take to write, but otherwise I'll just come up with the concept and go.

Not sure if you wanted an answer from me or writers in general, but the first person who replied isn't me. I can take a crack at answering, though.

Simple answer, I have notes.
On your specific question, no I don't do anything resembling worksheet or list out all the beats. On the plotter/pantser scale, I lean more towards pantsing. Especially in the beginning of a story's life, but after months of work on it I know the major points I want to hit to get to the ending I've chosen. How I get there ends up changing from what I initially plan, but I write while doing those changes. It's resulted in a lot of scrapped and binned writing but that doesn't bother me.
My notes are mostly about characters and relevant details that may never make it into the story, things about their lives and ties to other characters. I'll sometimes sketch out the rough idea of what I want to happen, leave it at the end of the document I'm working in, and inevitably do something fairly different but still in the same direction. I even write out of order sometimes. Get the scene that's farther ahead down and work towards it, changing what I need to when I hit the pre-written scene. Usually I do this with lewds. Leading up to lewds is hard. Wedding The Dragon stalled in the baths for nearly a month.

I've got a grasp of the characters and good memory for what I want to happen, I guess. I advocate for trying new methods to find what works for you, and not to be afraid to fail in the experimentation.

>>29255603
I've heard of people who can completely pants a story from start to end, but I'm not one. I've met more people who use posterboard with notecards and string and spend months planning out their stories than pure pantsers. I can start a story with no idea what anything is or who the characters are, wKw and AFaW are both children of that. That ignorance doesn't last long, maybe 1000 words.

If it didn't interfere with my writing I'd do it myself.
My tastes lean to longform with plots outside the sex.
I fear my opinions would harm the objective review of things I feel are less readable like greentext, or the snowflake replacement of character development with obscure species traits.

So here's a go at it.
>In Opposition - Act 1
https://pastebin.com/0vx5TuDv

If you're going to do fantasy, worldbuilding is a must. So many stories start with a pursuit or exile. Score a point for answering enough of the question, and not completely. Again, strange bedfellows. Humans and kobolds wouldn't normally interact, but it's work together or die.

The not-quite-perfect is far smaller than Kayl. The reader starts with the human male Irven. Paragraphs flip between him and the kobold Kayl. Technically, I felt the dialogue was stronger than the action. It's not a flaw, more a result of style and POV. No one has a perfect balance.
While I write more often in first person, third is extremely flexible despite what some writing guides claim. A writer can play all kinds of perspective tricks if they keep attribution straight.
So even though I only read through the first part, it left me wondering about the role of dragons in this setting and their effect on the narration's point of view. Combined with two outcasts against the standard fantasy abuse of power scenario, there's enough mystery to tip the scales in favor of continuing.

I've said this before: if you're better than the worst dross I've seen out of a professional publisher then you keep my attention. Mattariel far exceeds that, and it's enough to guarantee I want more.
